Here's how to handle each scenario:

### 1. Windows-only — `[TestMethod]` + OS check

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void RegistryTest()
{
    if (!OperatingSystem.IsWindows())
        Assert.Inconclusive("Requires Windows.");

    // ... registry code
}
```

Or with a custom attribute using `ITestDataSource` / condition, but `Assert.Inconclusive` is the simplest built-in approach.

### 2. Skip in CI — environment guard

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GpuTest()
{
    if (Environment.GetEnvironmentVariable("CI") == "true")
        Assert.Inconclusive("Skipped in CI — requires local GPU.");

    // ... GPU code
}
```

### 3. Flaky external API — `[Retry]`

MSTest v3+ has a built-in retry attribute:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[Retry(3)] // retries up to 3 times on failure
public async Task WeatherApiTest()
{
    var result = await _weatherClient.GetForecastAsync("Seattle");
    Assert.IsNotNull(result);
}
```

> For MSTest v2, you'd need a custom `IRetryAnalyzer`-style attribute or use [Polly](https://github.com/App-vNext/Polly) inside the test.

### 4. Cleanup even on failure — `[TestCleanup]` or `try/finally`

```csharp
private string? _tempFile;

[TestInitialize]
public void Setup()
{
    _tempFile = Path.GetTempFileName();
}

[TestCleanup] // runs even if the test throws
public void Cleanup()
{
    if (_tempFile != null && File.Exists(_tempFile))
        File.Delete(_tempFile);
}

[TestMethod]
public void TempFileTest()
{
    File.WriteAllText(_tempFile!, "data");
    // ... assertions
}
```

For one-off cases, `try/finally` inside the test works too.

---

**Summary of key MSTest mechanisms:**

| Scenario | Approach |
|---|---|
| Platform-specific | `Assert.Inconclusive()` with OS check |
| Skip in CI | `Assert.Inconclusive()` with env var check |
| Flaky/retry | `[Retry(N)]` (MSTest v3+) |
| Guaranteed cleanup | `[TestCleanup]` or `try/finally` |

`Assert.Inconclusive` marks the test as **skipped/warning** rather than passed or failed, so your results stay accurate.
